### Personal Locator Beacons (PLBs)

**How they work:**
- Transmit on 406 MHz frequency monitored by international COSPAS-SARSAT system
- Signal detected by satellites, relayed to rescue coordination centers
- Include GPS for precise location
- One-way communication only

**Specifications:**
- Battery life: 24-48 hours of continuous transmission
- No subscription required
- Must be registered with NOAA (US) or equivalent
- Waterproof, float-capable designs available

**When to use:**
- Life-threatening emergencies requiring immediate rescue
- Not for non-emergency communication
- One button activation

### Satellite Messengers

**Types:**
| Device | Network | Two-Way | Subscription |
|--------|---------|---------|--------------|
| Garmin inReach | Iridium | Yes | Required |
| SPOT | Globalstar | Limited | Required |
| Zoleo | Iridium + Cell | Yes | Required |
| Somewear | Iridium | Yes | Required |

**Features:**
- SOS button for emergencies
- Two-way text messaging
- Tracking/breadcrumb trail
- Check-in messages
- Weather forecasts (some models)

**Limitations:**
- Require clear sky view
- Subscription costs ($15-50+/month)
- Battery dependent
- Message length limits

### Cell Phones

**Maximizing usefulness:**
- Enable airplane mode to conserve battery
- Seek high ground for signal
- Text messages may work when voice fails
- WiFi calling if any network available
- Many phones still reach 911 on any carrier signal

**Limitations:**
- Coverage highly variable
- Battery drain in cold
- Fragile in wilderness conditions
- False sense of security

## Manual Signaling Methods

### Whistles

**Proper use:**
- Three blasts = distress signal
- Pause between sets to listen for response
- Conserves voice (yelling exhausting)
- Audible up to 1 mile

**Recommendations:**
- Pealess whistles work when wet
- Attach to pack or clothing
- Practice signal pattern

### Signal Mirrors

**Technique:**
- Hold mirror close to eye
- Extend other hand toward target
- Create V with fingers, place target in V
- Tilt mirror to flash light through V
- Sweep slowly to cover area

**Effectiveness:**
- Visible up to 10+ miles on clear days
- Works for aircraft and ground searchers
- Requires practice
- Useless in overcast conditions

### Ground-to-Air Signals

**Standard symbols:**
| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| X | Requires medical assistance |
| V | Require assistance |
| Y | Yes (affirmative) |
| N | No |
| Arrow | Traveling this direction |

**Construction:**
- Minimum 10 feet long, larger if possible
- High contrast with surroundings
- Use rocks, logs, stomped snow, clothing
- Maintain until rescue

### Fire and Smoke Signals

**Distress configuration:**
- Three fires in triangle (100 feet apart)
- Three columns of smoke

**Maximizing visibility:**
- Daytime: Add green vegetation for smoke
- Nighttime: Keep flames high
- Avoid during fire danger conditions

### International Distress Signal

**Six signals per minute, one minute pause, repeat:**
- Six whistle blasts
- Six flashlight flashes
- Six smoke puffs (if controllable)
- Rescuers respond with three signals

## Communication Planning

### Pre-Trip Preparation

**Before departing:**
1. Register devices (PLB registration mandatory)
2. Test all equipment
3. Charge batteries
4. Leave trip plan with emergency contact
5. Know your device capabilities and limitations

**Trip plan should include:**
- Planned route and timeline
- Expected check-in schedule
- Emergency contact information
- Vehicle location and description
- When to initiate search

### When to Signal for Help

**Appropriate SOS activation:**
- Serious injury requiring evacuation
- Life-threatening illness
- Lost with no ability to self-rescue
- Trapped by conditions (flood, avalanche)
- Imminent survival threat

**Consider alternatives first:**
- Can you solve the problem yourself?
- Is the situation actually life-threatening?
- Can you self-evacuate with effort?
- Will conditions improve soon?

### Working with Rescuers

**After SOS activation:**
1. Stay in place (unless immediate danger)
2. Continue signaling visually
3. Prepare landing zone if possible
4. Keep device on and check for messages
5. Conserve battery if response will be delayed

**Information to provide:**
- Exact location (coordinates if possible)
- Nature of emergency
- Number of people and conditions
